\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.1}{\ignorespaces The timeline of how the paradigm of the collaboration between human and AI coding assistants shifts from script-level static code generation to project-level coding agent.\relax }}{1}{figure.caption.4}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.1}{\ignorespaces The standard pipeline for code translation (colored in light grey) and the CMTrans pipeline (colored in pink). The comparable corpora are both naturally occurring and model generated. We generate multiple references by CMTrans\xspace . \relax }}{15}{figure.caption.6}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.2}{\ignorespaces An example of parallel and comparable data. Parallel examples are line-by-line aligned. Programs in a comparable example may have different algorithms and structures (e.g., global code vs. class in this case), but may still contain lines that can be matched, as highlighted in pink, blue, and yellow.\relax }}{15}{figure.caption.7}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.3}{\ignorespaces Perplexity of validation set during finetuning.\relax }}{16}{figure.caption.8}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.4}{\ignorespaces An example of CMTrans\xspace for Java-to-Python translation. We compare the pipeline of CMTrans\xspace (\textit {red}) to the standard pipeline (\textit {grey}) of code translation (e.g., finetuned CodeT5, \citealt {codet5}) and the self-supervision-and-fine-tuning method (\textit {purple}) of TransCoder-ST (\citealt {transcoderST}).\relax }}{18}{figure.caption.9}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.5}{\ignorespaces Translation results with different amount of parallel data. We mark the relative gain of CMTrans\xspace over CodeT5.\relax }}{24}{figure.caption.14}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.6}{\ignorespaces Number of unique correct translations in 20 candidates for each test example. We use beam search for each method, so the generated candidates are guaranteed to be distinct.\relax }}{26}{figure.caption.17}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.7}{\ignorespaces Effect of the size of comparable corpora.\relax }}{26}{figure.caption.18}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.8}{\ignorespaces Effect of the max number of references for each example.\relax }}{27}{figure.caption.19}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.9}{\ignorespaces Case study: a comparable example generated by our method with an NL-to-code generation model. We highlight the lines in the Java program and the generated Python program that can be matched.\relax }}{28}{figure.caption.20}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.1}{\ignorespaces We can use the coding environments built by \textsc {RepoST}\xspace for training and evaluation. We first apply the code generation model to generate candidate solutions with the original repository as context. Then we evaluate the solutions by executing the evaluation script built by \textsc {RepoST}\xspace . For evaluation, we directly compute Pass@$k$ scores. For training, we add all successful solutions to the train set and further finetune the model. \relax }}{30}{figure.caption.21}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.2}{\ignorespaces The \textsc {RepoST}\xspace coding environment construction framework. We sandbox the target function and its dependencies to a separate evaluation script for execution, which avoids building the entire repository. We design careful quality control strategies with iterative quality improvement and post-filtering. The outcome of \textsc {RepoST}\xspace is a set of executable repo-level coding environments, which can be used for training and evaluation.\relax }}{32}{figure.caption.22}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.3}{\ignorespaces An example where the LLM successfully creates a mock class, \texttt {Mock\_API}, to replace real external API calls. In this way, while the function body of the target function \texttt {API\_call} remains exactly the same as in the original codebase, it can be executed without making real API calls. \relax }}{33}{figure.caption.23}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.4}{\ignorespaces (a) Pass@1 scores on RepoEval with different numbers of training examples. (b) Pass@1 scores on RepoEval with different methods to sample 2,000 training examples. Sample-by-Example has a broader repository coverage and achieves better Pass@1. The performance is further enhanced with RFT (Distill). \relax }}{41}{figure.caption.29}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.1}{\ignorespaces (\textit {\textbf {Left}}) We decompose general coding agent tasks into a set of intermediate components and compute the percentage of agent actions spent on each component. Our training tasks partially cover verification and fully cover reasoning, repository exploration, and implementation, which consist of around 68\% of the actions. \textit {(\textbf {Right})} Example actions for each component. Compared to a baseline training method, SWE-Gym\nobreakspace {}\cite {swegym}, training with our \textsc {Hybrid-Gym}\xspace significantly reduces failures due to insufficient reasoning, insufficient exploration, and failed file editing, improving the final resolved rate on SWE-Bench Verified from 10.6\% to 15.0\%. \relax }}{47}{figure.caption.31}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.2}{\ignorespaces The error analysis of different methods on 50 instances sampled from SWE-Bench Verified.\relax }}{49}{figure.caption.34}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.3}{\ignorespaces Scaling law analysis. Performance on SWE-bench Verified improves consistently as training data size increases from around 5\% (250 trajectories) to 100\% (4.4k trajectories).\relax }}{55}{figure.caption.38}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.4}{\ignorespaces Controlled experiments on training data characteristics. (a)\nobreakspace {}\textbf {Output Format:} Removing the file editing actions (\texttt {str\_replace}) from function localization trajectories causes a large drop in SWE-bench resolution rate. (b)\nobreakspace {}\textbf {Repo-Exploration:} script-level code generation (LCB) does not effectively transfer to repo-level issue-solving and even underperforms documentation generation, a simple repo-level task. (c)\nobreakspace {}\textbf {Task Complexity:} Transfer improves as training tasks become more complex. (d)\nobreakspace {}\textbf {Trajectory Complexity:} With a fixed data size, training on longer (more agent steps) trajectories substantially improves downstream performance.\relax }}{58}{figure.caption.41}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.5}{\ignorespaces Effect of teacher model and data selection. (a) Effect of \textbf {sampling strategy} at fixed training budget. Repository diversity improves training but using the same repositories as in evaluation does not. (b) training on issue localization trajectories with different \textbf {teacher models}. o3-mini (edited) indicates the same set of trajectories as o3-mini, but with text and action steps combined. \relax }}{60}{figure.caption.42}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.1}{\ignorespaces Examples of the stages of coding tasks and the strategies to complete each stage. We design the stages by improving the task decomposition in Hybrid-Gym\nobreakspace {}\cite {hybrid-gym}, which are generally shared across different coding tasks. To define the strategies for each stage, we first use an LLM to categorize the agent steps into different stages, and then we summarize the purpose of each action. We keep improving the set of strategies when we discover agent steps that cannot be covered by existing strategies.\relax }}{67}{figure.caption.45}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.2}{\ignorespaces An example of how we represent trajectories at different abstraction levels. We show the categorization of each agent step in the format of ``stage label (strategy label)''. Note that the agent step can be categorized into multiple stages and strategies.\relax }}{68}{figure.caption.46}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.1}{\ignorespaces \textit {(Left)} The framework to train an evaluator, \textsc {FenCE}\xspace , by augmenting public datasets with textual critiques and more diverse knowledge sources. We show the details in \autoref {fig:evaluator_train}. \textit {(Right)} The framework to improve model factuality with \textsc {FenCE}\xspace . We construct training data by leveraging \textsc {FenCE}\xspace to revise and score the generator's responses. Details of response revision are shown in \autoref {fig:revise}.\relax }}{78}{figure.caption.48}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.2}{\ignorespaces Framework of evaluator training. (\textit {left}) Existing public datasets for evaluator training. Each example contains a claim, a source document, and the ground truth (GT) label of whether the claim is supported by the document. (\textit {Right}) We augment the datasets with textual critiques and more diverse source documents obtained by tools. We use zero-shot Llama-3-70B-chat as the instruction-tuned model in our experiments.\relax }}{79}{figure.caption.49}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.3}{\ignorespaces The framework to revise model responses without introducing lesser-known facts. We iteratively (1) use \textsc {FenCE}\xspace to evaluate the factuality of each claim, (2) replace false information (if any) with the correct fact or remove it from the response, depending on whether it corresponds to a lesser-known fact, and (3) continue generating the next passage. For every claim, we prompt the generator ``\textit {Is this claim factual?}'' without providing any source documents. If the generator outputs \textit {``unknown''}, we assume that the claim corresponds to a lesser-known fact. \relax }}{81}{figure.caption.50}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.4}{\ignorespaces Statistics of generated responses, where we group the prompts by the popularity of the person to write biography for, as labeled in the FActScore dataset. We compare zero-shot Llama3-8B-chat (denoted as \textit {``Base Model''}), SFT + \textsc {FenCE}\xspace (\textit {``SFT''}), and our method, Edit/Remove + Coarse (\textit {``DPO''}).\relax }}{88}{figure.caption.55}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.5}{\ignorespaces The factuality of claims with different topics, where we pre-define the topics and use Llama3-70B-chat to predict whether each claim covers any topic(s).\relax }}{88}{figure.caption.56}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.6}{\ignorespaces Hyper-parameter analysis. We investigate how percentage of facts changes (a) as number of iterations to revise candidate responses increases, and (b) with different numbers of preferred responses for each prompt. \relax }}{89}{figure.caption.57}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {8.1}{\ignorespaces Examples of high-level planning and low-level implementation in coding tasks by our definition. We define ``high-level planning'' as the process of producing intermediate steps about what should be done and in what order, where the intermediate steps do not need to be executable and hence do not have to be syntactically correct. We define ``low-level implementation'' as the process of generating concrete executable actions to perform the intermediate steps. The challenge is to generate the action that precisely follows the high-level planning and has the correct syntax (i.e., so that the action can be successfully executed to obtain outputs).\relax }}{95}{figure.caption.61}%
